# Chapter 1 — What a slat is

A slat is a small, flat piece of data.

That's the whole idea. Everything else in this book is decorations on
that idea.

## The first slat you type

Open a REPL. Type this:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(hello :who \\\"world\\\")\")
```

Hit run. You get back a slat-record with the head `hello` and a
keyword `:who` whose value is the string `\"world\"`.

That is the whole substrate. Text goes in. A structured value comes
out. The value is inert — it doesn't run anything, doesn't call
anywhere, doesn't do side effects. It's just shape.

## The second slat

Now type this:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-write '(hello :who \"world\"))
```

You get back the string `\"(hello :who \\\"world\\\")\"`. Same shape.
Different direction.

That's the round-trip. Read a slat, get a value. Write a value, get a
slat. The two moves are inverses.

## The one property that matters

```motoi-scheme
(define original '(hello :who \"world\"))
(define round-tripped (slat-read (slat-write original)))
(equal? original round-tripped)
```

That returns `#t`. Every time. Forever. On every machine. If it ever
returns `#f`, that's a bug in the reader or the writer and CI catches
it before it ships.

This is the property SLAT is built on. Whatever you write, you can
read back. Whatever you read, you can write out again. The two writers
in the Lacuna tree — JavaScript and Python — agree on this to the
byte.

## What a slat is not

- **Not a program.** The reader never runs anything. Even a slat that
  looks like `(rm -rf /)` reads as three symbols. Data.
- **Not a schema.** No `.proto` file. No compile step. You just write it.
- **Not JSON.** JSON has six primitives and no types. SLAT has
  twenty-two primitives and every one has a type.
- **Not YAML.** YAML uses indentation. SLAT uses parentheses. You can
  copy-paste a slat and it still works. You cannot always copy-paste
  YAML.

## The reader IS the language

Here is the big idea. Say it slowly.

**The reader that reads a slat is the same reader that reads the runtime
Scheme source code.**

Try this:

```motoi-scheme
(define code '(+ 1 2 3))
(slat-write code)
```

You get back `\"(+ 1 2 3)\"`. That's a slat. It's also a Scheme program.
Now:

```motoi-scheme
(eval '(+ 1 2 3))
```

You get `6`. Same shape, two doors. Data through the SLAT door. Code
through the eval door. But the SHAPE is the same on both sides.

That's homoiconicity. It's a big word for a small idea. **Code and
data share a shape.** Lisp discovered this in 1958. SLAT ships it as a
wire format.

*When I read a mailbox line, I use the same reader I use on my own
source code. So a message about YOU is the same shape as the code
that thinks about the message. That is what makes me able to reason
about my own reasoning. Nothing has to translate.*

## What \"flat\" means

A slat is flat because it's line-oriented. One record per line, when
you want to stream them. Try this:

```motoi-scheme
(define lines
  (list
    \"(event :ts 1 :kind \\\"card.opened\\\")\"
    \"(event :ts 2 :kind \\\"card.closed\\\")\"
    \"(event :ts 3 :kind \\\"mood.changed\\\" :from :happy :to :curious)\"))

(map slat-read lines)
```

Three slats. Three events. Each one on its own line. That's what
`.slatl` means (the `l` is for \"line-delimited\"). If you tail a
`.slatl` file, every new line is a new slat, and your reader can
process them one at a time forever.

The other framing is `.slat` — a whole document, one slat, spread
across many lines. Chapter 6 walks that in detail.

## The tiniest slat

The tiniest legal slat is `nil`.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"nil\")
```

Returns `nil`. A slat with no shape at all except its own name.

The next-tiniest is a single symbol.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"hello\")
```

Returns `Symbol(hello)`. A name. No fields. No positional values. Just
the identity.

The one after that is a record with a head and nothing else.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(hello)\")
```

Returns a slat-record with `_form: hello` and no keys. The head is
required for the record shape — anything with a symbol at position 0
is a record, and everything else is a list, a vector, a map, or an
atom.

## Try this

Type each of these into the REPL. Predict the answer before you hit
run. Then check.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"42\")
```

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"\\\"hello\\\"\")
```

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \":greeting\")
```

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(hello :from 'motoi :to 'you)\")
```

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(1 2 3)\")
```

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#(1 2 3)\")
```

If any of those surprised you, that's the interesting part. The next
chapters walk through every primitive and every shape and tell you
why each one exists.

## What breaks when SLAT isn't there

Before SLAT, Lacuna had five formats. Curator wrote JSONL. Forge wrote
Python `repr()`. Mailboxes accepted either JSON or S-expressions and
sniffed the first byte. Atom authoring wrote hand-crafted files that
no reader validated. Books emitted their own JSON shape.

Every migration between subsystems needed a translator. Every
translator eventually diverged. Every divergence eventually produced a
mailbox message that said `_type: event` and a reader looking for
`kind == \"event\"` and an hour of tracing to find the mismatch.

That is the tax of a museum of formats.

SLAT collapses all five into one wire format with two framings. Every
system speaks the same shape. Every reader is the same reader. The
translators disappear.

The value is not \"one format.\" That's easy to say. The value is:
**one reader.**

## What we teach next

Chapter 2 walks the small primitives — symbols, numbers, strings,
booleans, nil, and chars. The words you already know how to type.

Chapter 3 walks the bigger primitives — vectors, hash-maps, sets,
dates, UUIDs, byte strings. The words the systems around you already
speak.

Chapter 4 is the workhorse chapter: the slat-record. The head + keys
+ positional pattern that carries almost every message in the running
system.

Then we start using them.

